about the competition:¶

The competition is simple: use machine learning to create a model that predicts which passengers survived the Titanic shipwreck.

The sinking of the Titanic is one of the most infamous shipwrecks in history.

On April 15, 1912, during her maiden voyage, the widely considered unsinkable RMS Titanic sank after colliding with an iceberg. Unfortunately, there werent enough lifeboats for everyone onboard, resulting in the death of 1502 out of 2224 passengers and crew.

While there was some element of luck involved in surviving, it seems some groups of people were more likely to survive than others.

In this challenge, I will try to answer the question: what sorts of people were more likely to survive? using passenger data (ie name, age, gender, socio-economic class, etc).

In our assignment we will try to identify types of characteristics that can help us understand what the identity of the people who survived and those who did not survive looks like.

In order to answer the central question, we have like properties in the data that we will use:

survival Survival 0 = No, 1 = Yes

  • Survival: 0 = No, 1 = Yes ------ the target
  • Pclass: 1 = 1st, 2 = 2nd, 3 = 3rd
  • Sex: Male or Female
  • Ticket: Ticket number
  • Fare: Passenger fare
  • Cabin: Cabin number
  • Embarked: Port of Embarkation

function for labeled features - Onehotencoding

In [16]:
def labeled(col,train=train,test=test):
  enc = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore')
  train_ON = pd.DataFrame(enc.fit_transform(train[[col]]).toarray(),columns=pd.get_dummies(train[col],prefix=col).columns)
  test_ON = pd.DataFrame(enc.transform(test[[col]]).toarray(),columns=train_ON.columns)

  train = train.join(train_ON)
  test = test.join(train_ON)
  return train,test

train,test=labeled('Name')
train,test=labeled('Embarked',train,test)

age_full = train[train.Age.isna() == False].drop(['Cabin'],axis=1)
X = age_full.drop(['Age'],axis=1) 

sd = StandardScaler()
X = pd.DataFrame(sd.fit_transform(X),columns=X.columns)[age_full.drop('Age',axis=1).corrwith(y_Survived)[abs(age_full.drop('Age',axis=1).corrwith(y_Survived))>corr_val].index]
columns_X = X.columns

y = age_full.Age
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.1, random_state=101)

df_age_statics = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Regressor','MSE train','MSE test'])

for model in reggresors: 
  model = model.fit(X_train, y_train)
  preds = model.predict(X_test)
  error_train = mean_squared_error(model.predict(X_train),y_train)
  error_test = mean_squared_error(y_test,preds)
  df_age_statics = df_age_statics.append({'Regressor':str(model).split('(')[0],'MSE train':error_train,'MSE test':error_test},ignore_index=True)
df_age_statics = df_age_statics.append({'Regressor':'MEAN','MSE train':mean_squared_error(np.ones(len(y_train))*train.Age.mean(),y_train),'MSE test':mean_squared_error(np.ones(len(y_test))*train.Age.mean(),y_test)},ignore_index=True)
df_age_statics = df_age_statics.append({'Regressor':'MEDIAN','MSE train':mean_squared_error(np.ones(len(y_train))*train.Age.median(),y_train),'MSE test':mean_squared_error(np.ones(len(y_test))*train.Age.median(),y_test)},ignore_index=True)

df_age_statics.plot(x='Regressor',y=['MSE train','MSE test'],kind='bar',figsize=(20,7))

Selectiong features - in two ways!¶

We can also use Scikit-learn RFECV to use CV and choose the best number of features on this dataset. The default CV is 5-fold cross-validation. We will enter the Scikit-learn RepeatedKFold to repeat each KFold a few times with different splits.

In [60]:
# find best subset of features on this dataset

from sklearn.feature_selection import RFECV
from sklearn.model_selection import RepeatedKFold

X_encoded = pd.DataFrame(StandardScaler().fit_transform(train),columns=train.columns)

selector = RFECV(SGDClassifier(random_state=1), cv=RepeatedKFold(n_splits=30, n_repeats=30, random_state=1)).fit(X_encoded, y_Survived )

    KNeighborsClassifier(5),

    RandomForestClassifier(),
    SGDClassifier(),
    LogisticRegression()]

 
df_Survived_statics = pd.DataFrame(columns=["Classifier", "Accuracy train","Accuracy test",'CE train','CE test'])

for clf in classifiers:
  name = clf.__class__.__name__
  clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
  train_predictions = clf.predict(X_test)
  acc_train = accuracy_score(clf.predict(X_train), y_train)
  acc_test = accuracy_score(y_test, train_predictions)
  ce_train = log_loss(clf.predict(X_train),y_train)
  ce_test = log_loss(clf.predict(X_test),y_test)

  df_Survived_statics = df_Survived_statics.append({"Classifier":name, "Accuracy train":acc_train,"Accuracy test":acc_test,'CE train':ce_train,'CE test':ce_test},ignore_index=True)

The history of my subbmission:

I tried in several ways, in a huge variety of models.¶

I fronted the missing data with machine learning models! - This is not a common thing.¶

This approach resulted in a very large project!¶

There are two models of classification problem here - of cabin and of survivors.¶

There are models here with predictions also for the regression problem for the purpose of filling the age column¶

Summary:¶

There are things to improve like to explore in more depth the various hyper parameters of each of the models and measure the results :)

In conclusion¶

There are many things for a greater chance to survive. Being a female or a child will increase you chances. If you have a higher class ticket you have the more chance of surviving athan a third class ticket. As for a man, you are more likely to survive if embark in Cherbourg compare to Southampton or Queenstown. If you also travel with 1 or 3 people than 0 or more than 3 your survival chances are greater. The younger you are will also make your survival chance. So it comes down to many things to surivive on the titanic.
